\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 CLASS MEETINGS
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 9:30 AM - 12:00 PM Thursdays, 1070 ISR-Thompson (Michigan) and 1208 Lefrak Hall (Maryland), starting January 8, 2026\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 PRE-REQUISITES
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Completion of courses in applied sampling and data collection methods OR completion of an introduction to survey methodology course OR permission of instructors.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 COURSE CONTENT
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 The Survey Design Seminar is a practical training element for students in the University of Maryland\'92s Joint Program in Survey Methodology and the University of Michigan\'92s Program in Survey and Data Science Masters\'92 degree programs. It prepares students to work with real-world clients on methodological problems as they develop skills in consulting for survey design, data collection, analysis, and data science. Instruction is provided in consulting skills, professional presentations, developing research proposals in response to requests for proposals, and professional conduct.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 COURSE EXPECTATIONS
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 This course meets weekly simultaneously at the University of Maryland and the University of Michigan. Typical class sessions are two and one-half hours and usually include lecture and discussion. For the client and student presentation sessions (see\'a0
\f2\i Team Assignments
\f0\i0 \'a0below) on January 22, February 19, and April 2, class sessions are expected to be at least three hours.\cb1 \
\cb2 Regular attendance at class sessions is required, and in-person attendance at all class sessions is a requirement of the program. If a student is unable to attend a particular class session, they are required to notify the instructors via email at least 15 minutes before the start of the class session.\cb1 \
\cb2 This is a two-campus course, and the instructors are both at the University of Michigan. They each expect to travel to the University of Maryland once during the semester.\cb1 \
\cb2 The course will utilize the University of Michigan Canvas course site system. Each student will be registered on the Michigan Canvas system. The course web site will include weekly overviews of what is expected for the coming week, materials to be read for class, the course daily schedule, assignments, facilities for submission of assignments, and facilities for return of marked assignments.\cb1 \
\cb2 Given the nature of the instructor advising role with each team (see below), instructors will not post specific office hours. Students wanting to meet with an instructor, individually or as a team, should schedule appointments by email or in person.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 \cb2 \'a0Client Consulting Team Project
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 The instructors have recruited six clients (see Client Summaries below) with methodological projects that need survey and data science expert consulting. The course web site has folders with background materials provided by each client. All students are expected, as part of ungraded Task 1, to read the background material for each client before the first class session on January 8. This background reading should serve as the basis for each student\'92s first and second client preference. Teams will be formed as much as possible on the basis of first preference. In cases where too many students prefer a particular client, instructors will first select students to be moved to another client as their second preference. If second preference cannot be met either, then randomly selected students will be assigned to a team to balance the size of the teams.\cb1 \
\cb2 Teams will be formed with students from both campuses. Teams will be responsible for organizing team meetings and designating team members to interact with the client. Each team will have one of the two instructors as a team adviser throughout the consulting process.\cb1 \
\cb2 Clients will be invited to a regular class session (January 22) to make a presentation about the methodological problem they would like addressed. All students will attend all client presentations. During and after the team\'92s client presentation, the team members will be expected to interact with the client, asking questions and attempting to understand fully the nature of the client\'92s methodological problems.\cb1 \
\cb2 Following the initial client meeting, instructors will meet with teams weekly in and outside of class to advise them about such tasks as developing conceptual understandings of the client\'92s problem, operationalizing conceptual measures, developing proposals on how to address client problems, reviewing relevant literature, developing a presentation of the team ideas, and so on. Instructors will be available for individual appointments with students on an \'93as needed\'94 basis.\cb1 \
\cb2 On February 19, clients will be invited back to the classroom to hear a preliminary 15 to 20-minute presentation by the team. On April 2, students will make a final 20-minute presentation to the client. In most cases, the students will submit to the client a set of slides outlining the results of their review, summarizing investigations, and discussing recommendations. There may be additional products such as a bibliography, draft questionnaire, or a sample design. Each student must give part of either the preliminary or final presentation.\cb1 \
\cb2 The following is a brief summary of the client projects; fuller descriptions are on the Canvas site:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\i\b \cf0 \cb2 Design surveys in two African countries concerning attitudes toward dual citizenship
\f1\i0 .
\f0\b0 \'a0We are designing a multi-country survey in West Africa on public opinions of dual citizenship. Prior research on these themes has been largely concentrated in the global North; recent experiences across Africa, however, demonstrate the potential contentiousness of citizens holding two nationalities on a variety of political and economic outcomes. A number of African governments have recently moved to either restrict or liberalize dual nationality policies, while there is also considerable variation in public support for these policies. In addition, over half of African countries prevent elected officials from holding multiple nationalities; in several cases, incumbent regimes have prevented opposition politicians with dual citizenship from running for office in the first place. Our project aims to probe when and why citizens support dual citizenship and whether nationality laws affecting political office holders shape popular perceptions of the democratic process more broadly. The surveys are planned for two countries \'96 C\'f4te d\'92Ivoire and Liberia\cb1 \

\f3\i\b \cb2 Evaluate the result of experiments to increase response rates.
\f0\i0\b0 \'a0The American Speech-Language-Hearing Association (ASHA) is a professional and credentialing association which currently has approximately 241,000 members and affiliates who are audiologists, speech-language pathologists, speech, language, and hearing scientists, audiology and speech-language pathology assistants, and students. The Surveys and Analysis Team (SAT) conducts 75-100 online surveys, 1-2 paper/pencil surveys, and several focus groups each year, with our members comprising almost all of the survey participants. As with most survey researchers, we have experienced a decline in survey participation over the last decade, especially within the last five years. We have completed many methodological experiments over the past few years that can include changes to messaging, modality, data collection methods, and reporting with the goal of increasing the engagement of our members in the survey process. However, we have only evaluated the success of these methods in isolation within a given survey and fielding year. We would like to look at these experiments more holistically and determine some overall recommendations related to improving member engagement in our surveys.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\i\b \cf0 \cb2 Assessing the Effectiveness of Alternative Contact and Recruitment Strategies for Survey Respondents
\f1\i0 .
\f0\b0 \'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 The Health and Retirement Survey (HRS) is a longitudinal panel study that began in 1992 at the Survey Research Center. It is a national sample of adults over the age of 50 and their spouses in the United States, and every six years a new birth cohort of adults aged 51-56 is recruited into the panel to replenish the sample.\'a0 The project seeks to develop a data collection protocol that will be applied in the recruitment and interviewing of these MGX persons between 2027 and 2028. We are open to the discussion of potential experiments designed to optimize the data collection protocol, since this fresh probability sample will be released in a series of sample replicates (each of which will be worked within a defined time window of 4-6 months). The project has provided a list of topics and challenges on which we would like to consult with the PSDS students.\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\i\b \cf0 \cb2 Evaluating the Usability of an Online Survey Instrument in Crisis Circumstances
\f0\i0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 The Panel Study of Income Dynamics (PSID) is one of the longest running surveys conducted by the Survey Research Center in ISR. Across almost six decades of data collection from an original sample and the succeeding generations of family members, the mode of interviewing has moved from face-to-face interviews with paper and pencil questionnaires to telephone interviews employing CATI systems to now employing an online questionnaire. The PSID research team is interested in an initial look at usability issues with the online application and how it may affect data quality. The purpose of this project would be to conduct the first steps of a more systematic usability review. This would involve further testing of the web instrument and a quantitative analysis of paradata such as interview timings and break off points. The student team would interact with the PSID leadership team and SMP faculty.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f3\i\b \cf0 \cb2 Analyze a Membership Survey and Suggest Strategies for Membership Engagement and Participation.\'a0
\f0\i0\b0 \'a0The Ann Arbor Rotary Club has a recent membership survey they would like analyzed, with the results converted to a strategy for continued membership engagement and survey response. They are interested in answers for the following questions, based on the analysis:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Which groups of members are most engaged or least engaged?\'a0 How can we improve member engagement and retention?\'a0 How can we recruit and retain members, especially younger professionals?\'a0 How can future surveys be improved? What questions or formats would yield more actionable data? Can we design a strategy for ongoing feedback and improvement?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Development of a Cross-national Survey of Consumer Attitudes.\'a0
\f0\b0 Survey Monkey is interested in developing survey items to measure consumer attitudes with a cross-national perspective. A client doing a project for a news organization wants to develop a survey to understand consumers\'92 personal financial sentiment today to develop into targeted articles for media publication. Their hypothesis is that consumers across various countries (specifically the US, UK, Canada and Australia) are experiencing financial strain, and need data to support this narrative.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Their main question is: how are consumers feeling about their personal finances today? They are looking for a comprehensive dive across various angles, including sentiment surrounding or related to job security, day-to-day spending, emergency savings and retirement. The client wants major life milestones taken into account, for example differences in sentiment and financial planning across gender, generations, and countries.\cb1 \
\cb2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 \cb2 Individual Proposal Writing Project
\f0\i0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 In the last third of the course, students will develop and write a response to a Request for Proposals (RFP) provided by the instructors. This will be an individual and not a team project activity. That is, students may\'a0
\f1\b not\'a0
\f0\b0 collaborate with other students on the development or writing of their proposal, and each student will receive an individual and not a team score for the proposal project (see \'93Grades\'94 below).\cb1 \
\cb2 The instructors will post the RFP on the Canvas site on March 13 (see Syllabus below). Students will read the RFP and one week later submit any questions they have to clarify the nature of the project described in the RFP. During the March 19 class session, the instructors will host a \'93Bidders\'92 Conference\'94 where they will answer student questions.\cb1 \
\cb2 Bidders\'92 Conference questions and answers will also be posted on Canvas after the March 19 class session. In addition, instructors will post three tools on Canvas to help students develop and write their proposals: 1) a survey design checklist and proposal outline covering the core elements students should consider in their proposal; 2) a GANTT chart spreadsheet template for recording tasks and their timelines for delivery; and 3) a budget spreadsheet template students can use to develop a budget for their proposal.\cb1 \
\cb2 The instructors will be available at the April 9 class session to answer student questions about their proposals. The individual student proposals are due April 15 and will be submitted via Canvas.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 \cb2 \'a0
\f1\i0\b TEXTBOOK AND READING
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 The principal text is\'a0
\f2\i Statistical Consulting
\f0\i0 , by Javier Cabrera and Andrew McDougall (Springer Science+ Business Media, 2002). You should focus on chapters 1 through 6 and 9, as indicated in the syllabus, referred to as C&M. This is an ebook that you can access through the University of Michigan Library. A second reading source is Alan Weiss,\'a0
\f2\i Getting Started in Consulting
\f0\i0 \'a0(Wiley, 4
\fs24 th
\fs32 \'a0Edition 2019), also available online and for purchase as an ebook, as indicated in the syllabus as AW\cb1 \
\cb2 Additional readings on consulting in statistical practice are also available in the Canvas Files folder \'93Readings.\'94 Reading assignments should be completed before class.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 GRADING
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Students will be evaluated on a number of team assignments and one individual assignment. Each team is responsible for one student submitting team assignments such as the preliminary and final presentation slide sets. Instructors will assign scores for each assignment to all team members.\cb1 \
\cb2 Most team submissions will be graded as check-plus (100), check (90), check-minus (80), and not submitted (0). Marked team submissions are due on the date indicated in the syllabus and will ordinarily be returned before the next class session.\cb1 \
\cb2 The preliminary and final presentations will each be scored on a 100-point basis.\'a0 These presentation scores will not use the \'93check\'94 marking system.\cb1 \
\cb2 The final project is an individual assignment to develop and write a proposal in response to a request for proposals (RFP), and it will be scored on a 100-point basis.\cb1 \
\cb2 There are seven ungraded tasks that all students are expected to complete.\cb1 \
\cb2 The final grade will be a weighted average of scores on the average of six team submissions (20% total), the team preliminary presentation (10%), the team final presentation (20%), and the individual proposal (50%).\cb1 \
\cb2 Near the end of the course, students will also complete a peer evaluation rating of the individual contributions that other team members made to the completion of the team project. If the peer evaluations for an individual are strong, unadjusted individual team score averages will be used to determine final grades. Otherwise, the instructors will adjust an individual\'92s average team score downward to reflect less than adequate contributions to the team project.\cb1 \
\cb2 Students may, no less than one hour before a submission is due, request permission to submit team or individual assignments late. Late submission permission is not guaranteed but is generally granted. If a submission is late, and there is no prior permission, team assignment or individual scores will be reduced by 30 points. Missing or incomplete assignments receive a score of zero.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Academic Misconduct
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 The University of Michigan community functions best when its members treat one another with honesty, fairness, respect, and trust. The college promotes the assumption of personal responsibility and integrity and prohibits all forms of academic dishonesty and misconduct. Being found responsible for academic misconduct will usually result in a grade sanction.\cb1 \
\cb2 Students are expected to adhere to the ethical standards at their respective university where they are registered. In general, instructors consider the presence of a student\'92s name on a document as the student\'92s pledge that the work presented is theirs alone. University academic integrity policies at both campuses have clear definitions of academic misconduct, including cheating and plagiarism, as well as disciplinary sanctions for academic misconduct. Cases of misconduct will be handled according to the respective campus rules and policies.\cb1 \
\cb2 Knowledge of these rules and policies is the responsibility of the student. Ignorance or lack of familiarity does not excuse misconduct.\cb1 \
\cb2 \'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 \cb2 Use of ChatGPT and other AI Tools
\f0\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \cb2 Instructors in this course may ask you to provide evidence of your learning through written work. When they do, the writing you submit must be of your own creation. Your writing will naturally be informed by other written work. When it is, you must be sure to acknowledge this influence through appropriate citation.\cb1 \
\cb2 In the past, the \'91other written work\'92 was always created by another human. These days, artificial intelligence (AI) tools can be used to generate text, code, and images in response to a prompt. Such automatically generated text is not your work and cannot be submitted as if it is.\cb1 \
\cb2 Work generated by AI tools like ChatGPT is a source that may inform your writing, just as books, papers, lecture notes, websites, and the results of Google searches can. As always, it\'92s your responsibility to assess the reliability of every source you use. In that context, you should be aware that the output of AI tools is constructed to sound plausible, and not checked by any expert. These results are often completely invented.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

